Origin and attribution
----------------------

ProxiPort is a continuation of the open-source remote-management project
rport (CloudRadar GmbH, 2020; RealVNC Limited, 2023) and its community
fork openrport (the openrport authors, 2024-2025). Both upstreams shipped
their source under the MIT License.

ProxiPort imports the upstream openrport Go server and agent tree. The
upstream MIT-licensed portions remain covered by their original MIT
terms (see LICENSE-MIT for the inherited notice). The combined work, as
distributed by Proximile LLC under the name ProxiPort, is
AGPL-3.0-or-later.


Scope of the fork
-----------------

ProxiPort forks ONLY the FOSS portion of the upstream tree. Specifically:

- We took the MIT-licensed Go server, agent, shared libraries, build
  scripts, and API documentation.
- We did NOT take the upstream `plus/` plugin scaffolding. The `plus/`
  directory in openrport existed only to load a closed-source proprietary
  plugin binary (the "Plus" plugin, distributed separately by the previous
  upstream maintainer under a proprietary licence). That binary was never
  in any source repository, was never part of the FOSS code, and is not
  present in ProxiPort in any form. The `plus/` scaffolding was deleted
  from the ProxiPort tree along with every `IsPlusEnabled` capability
  gate. ProxiPort has no plugin-host substitute and does not attempt to
  reimplement the proprietary Plus features as gated commercial add-ons;
  features that previously lived behind the gate will be reimplemented in
  the open under AGPL.
- We did NOT take the upstream Vue.js / Nuxt frontend. The upstream
  shipped that frontend only as a prebuilt JavaScript bundle; the source
  was never published. Because the source was never available, we could
  not fork it, and we made no attempt to. The frontend in `frontend/` is
  an original SvelteKit / TypeScript / Tailwind SPA written from scratch
  for ProxiPort by Proximile LLC, AGPL-licensed along with the rest of
  the tree.

In short: every line of ProxiPort source is either inherited MIT code
from rport/openrport (subject to the original MIT licence as preserved in
LICENSE-MIT) or original AGPL-licensed code written for ProxiPort. No
proprietary code, no closed-source binary, and no capability-gated logic
is present anywhere in the ProxiPort source tree.


Bundled third-party FOSS components
-----------------------------------

ProxiPort uses the following FOSS components without modification. Each
retains its own license. See the upstream project for the authoritative
copy.

- jpillora/chisel — MIT (basis of the SSH-over-WebSocket tunnel
  transport, by way of the upstream rport fork).
- noVNC — MPL-2.0 (embedded VNC client used by the optional remote
  desktop feature).
- Apache Guacamole — Apache-2.0 (RDP/VNC/SSH gateway used by the
  optional remote desktop feature).
- Go module dependencies — see go.mod / go.sum and the LICENSE files of
  each module under the module cache. All are FOSS-licensed.
- npm devDependencies for the frontend — see frontend/package.json and
  the LICENSE files of each package under node_modules. All are
  FOSS-licensed.


